\chapter{Introduction}

\section{Purpose}
The software requirements specification is intended to provide a detailed explanation of the features and design specifications of this website. This document is intended for the stakeholders and developers of this website.

\section{Document Conventions}
This document follows a consistent structure and formatting style to make the requirements
clear and easy to reference. Section headings are numbered according to IEEE SRS
standards, with subsections used to break down specific requirements. 

Plain text is used for general descriptions. 
\textbf{Bold text} is used for emphasis on key terms or priorities. 

All functional requirements are labeled with the prefix \textbf{REQ-} followed by a number
(e.g., REQ-1, REQ-2) to provide a unique identifier for traceability. High-level priorities
defined in system features are inherited by their detailed requirements unless otherwise
stated. 

Fonts are standardized throughout the document for consistency, and requirements are
written in complete sentences to avoid ambiguity. 

\section{Intended Audience and Reading}
This SRS is designed to serve as an easy-to-understand framework for all stakeholders
involved with the BurnLab platform. It provides developers with a clear set of functional
and nonfunctional requirements to guide implementation. Project managers can use this
document to track progress and verify that all planned features align with business goals.
Marketing staff may refer to it to understand the scope of features and the value the
platform provides to end users. Testers will use the requirements to create test cases and
verify system functionality, while administrators and support staff can reference it for
understanding expected system behaviors.  

The document begins with an introduction and overall description of the product,
followed by detailed system features and functional requirements. These sections are
most useful to developers, testers, and managers who need a precise technical
understanding. The nonfunctional requirements and other requirements sections provide
guidance on performance, safety, security, and quality attributes, which are of interest to
both technical staff and project stakeholders.  

A recommended sequence for reading is to start with the Introduction (Section 1) to
understand the purpose and scope, proceed to the Overall Description (Section 2) for
context, then review the System Features (Section 3) for detailed requirements. Readers
concerned with long-term operation, maintainability, and compliance should pay special
attention to Other Nonfunctional Requirements (Section 4) and Other Requirements
(Section 5).


\section{Product Scope}
BurnLab would provide the meal and workout plans for customers to maintain a healthy lifestyle. The plan should be adaptable based on the preferences and characteristics of the users.

\section{References}
\textit{
}List any other documents or Web addresses to which this SRS refers. These may include user interface style guides, contracts, standards, system requirements specifications, use case
documents, or vision and scope documents. Provide enough information for the reader to access a copy of each reference, including title, author, version number, date, and source or location.

\chapter{Overall Description}

\section{Product Perspective}
BurnLab is a self-contained website. BurnLab will be an intermediary between sellers and buyers of products.  The system of this web application will use methods of interconnected relational databases. Our users will have simple-to-understand interfaces so that anyone can use the website without confusion or a lack of technical skills.\textit{
}

\section{Product Functions}

BurnLab provides users with the ability to create personalized fitness and nutrition experiences. The platform will collect basic profile information such as age, weight, height, and fitness goals, then use this data to generate customized workout and meal plans. Users will be able to log their daily progress, track performance over time, and receive updated recommendations as they progress in their fitness journey. The system will also function as a marketplace, where sellers such as trainers and nutritionists can upload their own programs, recipes, and plans for purchase. Buyers will be able to browse available plans, compare options, and make secure purchases through the platform. Administrative functions will include user management, content moderation, and maintaining platform security. In addition, BurnLab will allow guest visitors to preview limited content to encourage registration. These core functions: personalized plan generation, progress tracking, content marketplace, and administrative oversight will define the essential services BurnLab must deliver. 

\section{User Classes and Characteristics}
Buyers, Sellers, Admins, are the base user class which are going to be instated initially into the software. Buyers will have an email and password requirement to enter into the webstore's homepage. They will have access to the various meal plans and/or fitness plans sold by different sellers. In addition, sellers will have the ability to add and remove different products from our Webstore. Lastly, the Admin class is a general superuser with the ability to make direct contact with users and sellers, settling disputes and fixing bugs or errors in the buyer and seller experiences.\textit{ 
}

\section{Operating Environment}
BurnLab will be optimized for general web applications. Such as Chrome, Firefox, Edge, etc.\textit{ }

\section{Design and Implementation Constraints}
\textit{
}Burnlab is going to be using small scale servers, and as such, it will not be able to support a large number of users, as Amazon or eBay may be able to support.\textit{
}Burnlab will use Django, HTML, and CSS as the main languages for this project. As for the databases, we are using Firebase to serve as the cloud-hosted database. HTTPS and TLS encryption will be used to protect user data. Using hashing to protect data from bad actors and data leaks. Lastly, sellers must provide allergen data to alert any potential buyers of items to avoid.

\chapter{System Features}
\textit{}

\section{Profile Registry}
\begin{subs}
    \subsection{Description and priority}
    Allow a user to create an account using an email and password. This is high priority since it is required for any user interaction on the website.

    \subsection{Stimulus/Response Sequences}
    
    \textbf{ }
    \textbf{Profile as Admin}
    
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Admin navigates to ``Profile'' in the Admin Console.
        \item System loads stored details.
        \item Admin edits fields and saves changes.
        \item System validates and updates profile.
        \item System displays: ``Profile updated successfully.''
    \end{itemize}

    \textbf{Profile Request as Seller}
    
    \begin{itemize}
        \item User navigates to ``Apply as Seller.''
        \item User enters business name, address, and tax ID.
        \item User uploads verification documents.
        \item System validates required info.
        \item Application stored as ``Pending Review.''
        \item Notification: ``Your seller request is under review.''
    \end{itemize}

    \textbf{Seller Profile Denied – False Information}
    
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Admin reviews application.
        \item Detects false or misleading info.
        \item Clicks ``Deny'' and records reason.
        \item System updates status to ``Denied.''
        \item Seller notified: ``Your application was denied due to false information.''
    \end{itemize}

    \textbf{Seller Profile Denied – Business Does Not Exist}
    
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Admin reviews application.
        \item Cannot verify business existence.
        \item Clicks ``Deny'' with reason ``Business not found.''
        \item System updates status to ``Denied.''
        \item Seller notified: ``Your application was denied because the business could not be verified.''
    \end{itemize}

    \textbf{Profile as Buyer}
    
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Buyer navigates to ``My Profile.''
        \item System loads stored information.
        \item Buyer edits personal details.
        \item Buyer clicks ``Save.''
        \item System validates and updates record.
        \item Confirmation: ``Profile updated.''
    \end{itemize}

    \subsection{Functional Requirements}
    REQ-1: Given that both the email and the password meet required standards the system will accept a new user. \newline
    REQ-2: If there is an invalid email or password input send a message to the user. \newline
    REQ-3: Must have User, Seller, or Admin specifications.
\end{subs}


\section{Login and Logout System}
\textit{}
\begin{subs}

    \subsection{Description and priority}
    The login system feature will validate the user input credentials. This will be a high priority as it will be necessary for users and sellers to get access to the main functions.
    }
   \subsection{Stimulus/Response Sequences}

{Login as Seller}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Seller navigates to the BurnLab login page.
    \item Seller selects ``Login as Seller.''
    \item Seller enters email and password.
    \item System validates the credentials.
    \item If valid → redirect to Seller Dashboard.
    \item If invalid → display: ``Invalid login credentials.''
\end{itemize}

{Login as Buyer}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Buyer navigates to the BurnLab login page.
    \item Buyer selects ``Login as Buyer.''
    \item Buyer enters email and password.
    \item System verifies credentials.
    \item If valid → redirect to Homepage.
    \item If invalid → display: ``Email or password not recognized.''
\end{itemize}

{ Login as Admin }
\begin{itemize}
    \item Admin navigates to the BurnLab login page.
    \item Admin selects ``Login as Admin.''
    \item Admin enters email/username and password.
    \item System validates against Admin database.
    \item If valid → redirect to Admin Console.
    \item If invalid → display: ``Login failed.''
    \item If non-admin attempts → block and redirect to Homepage.
\end{itemize}

{Logout}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Any logged-in user (Buyer, Seller, or Admin) clicks ``Logout.''
    \item System ends the session and clears tokens.
    \item User is redirected to the login page.
    \item If inactive for 15 minutes → system automatically logs out and displays: ``Session expired.''
\end{itemize}

    \subsection{Functional Requirements}
    \textit{
    }REQ-4:\textit{ 
    }If the user inputs a valid email-password combination, they will be redirected to the homepage.\textit{\newline
 }   REQ-5: 
    If the email or password is incorrect the user will be sent an error message.\textit{\newline
    }
\end{subs}
\section{Marketplace}
\textit{}
\begin{subs}

    \subsection{Description and priority}
    The Marketplace is where users will view available products and add them to their cart for purchase; as such it is a high priority inclusion\textit{.\newline}
    
    \subsection{Stimulus/Response Sequences}
{Seller Requests to Put Product on the Market}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Seller navigates to ``Add Product.''
    \item Enters title, description, price, and stock.
    \item Uploads images.
    \item Submits product.
    \item System validates input and sets status to ``Pending Admin Approval.''
    \item Seller notified: ``Your product has been submitted for review.''
\end{itemize}

{ Admin Approves Product}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Admin reviews pending products.
    \item If compliant → clicks ``Approve.''
    \item System changes status to ``Active.''
    \item Product published to marketplace.
    \item Seller notified: ``Your product has been approved.''
\end{itemize}

{Admin Denies Product}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Admin reviews pending product.
    \item Finds violation or issue.
    \item Clicks ``Deny'' and enters reason.
    \item System updates status to ``Denied.''
    \item Seller notified: ``Your product was denied. Reason: [admin note].''
\end{itemize}

{Marketplace Quantity Updates}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Buyer views product listing.
    \item System displays stock quantity.
    \item Buyer adds item to cart.
    \item System reduces available quantity.
    \item If stock hits zero → mark as ``Sold Out.''
\end{itemize}

{Navigate to Marketplace Page}
\begin{itemize}
    \item User clicks ``Marketplace'' in navigation.
    \item System loads Marketplace page.
    \item User browses items with pagination and filters.
    \item User can return to Homepage at any time.
\end{itemize}
    
    \subsection{Functional Requirements}
    
     REQ-6: 
     User can add an item to the cart from the marketplace.\textit{\newline}
     REQ-7: 
     User can move between pages of the marketplace to view more stock.\textit{\newline}
     REQ-8:\textit{
     }User can move to the shopping cart from the marketplace\textit{.\newline}
     REQ-9: 
     User can move back to the homepage from the marketplace.\textit{\newline
     }
\end{subs}
\section{Order History}
\textit{}
\begin{subs}

    \subsection{Description and priority}
    Order History will include the information on all purchases and sales made through Burnlab; as such it will be listed as a high priority inclusion because it is the way any disputes will need to be handled.
    }
    \subsection{Stimulus/Response Sequences}

    \textbf{Buyer looking for reciept documentation}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Buyer clicks on the orderID among the list of orders.
        \item Buyer sees a pdf for the reciept as well as an invoice.
        \item Buyer selects to open the reciept pdf.
        \item Buyer searches using the search toolbar for another product he is interested in. 
    \end{itemize}
    \textbf{Seller needs to view order invoice} 
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Seller clicks to a previous page until he sees the first new order of the day 
        \item Seller finds among the listed order history multiple purchases so the seller goes through the orderIDs for processing.
        \item Seller opens the invoice and reciept documents for each to begin those order confirmations and their preparation. 
        \item Seller clicks to return to the homepage once they have finished their work and leaves their computer on by accident\
    \end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Seller is automatically logged out after a period of inactivity.
\end{itemize}
}
    \subsection{Functional Requirements}
    \textit{
    }REQ-10:
    User can move to the order history page from the homepage.\textit{\newline
    }REQ-11:
    User can move back to the homepage from the order history page.\textit{\newline
    }REQ-12: 
    User can see the OrderID and can click to view the invoice and receipt files.\textit{\newline
    
    }
\end{subs}
\section{Shopping Cart}
\textit{}
\begin{subs}

    \subsection{Description and priority}
    Lists selected items with their unique IDs and total price. This will be listed as high priority because it is the only place buyers can remove items from their cart and as such will be needed for basic functionality.
    
    \subsection{Stimulus/Response Sequences}
    \textit{
    }- User clicks to add the appropriate payment/shipping information into the appropriate boxes; now the user can type their information.\newline
    - User can click to pay recieving a unique orderID with the reciept and invoice sending the invoice also to the sellers.\newline
    - User clicks the homepage icon and goes to the homepage.\newline\textit{
    }
    
\subsection{User Makes Purchase}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Buyer clicks button to purchase items in cart
    \item System displays price and prompts user to input card info and address
    \item If given invalid card info → send message to buyer asking for valid
            info
    \item If buyer tries to proceed without an address → system sends message
            stating an address is required 
    \item If given valid card info and address → system does a final check if all
            items are in stock and card has enough money for the purchase.
            \item   If card is short on money → system sends message declining card 
            \item If any items are no longer in stock → buyer is informed that
            something went wrong 
            \item Buyer is informed that "Your order has been placed"
\end{itemize}
    
    \subsection{Functional Requirements}
    REQ-13: 
    The user would be able to check out and purchase all items in cart. They would have to input unique payment info to confirm the purchase.\newline
    REQ-14: 
    The user would be able to remove any item from the cart.\newline
    REQ-15:
    The User may click back to the homepage from the shopping cart.\newline\textit{
    }
\end{subs}

\section{Homepage}
\textit{}
\begin{subs}

    \subsection{Description and priority}
    The homepage is the hub to reach any page that may need to be reached, as well as it is the only page you can logout on. For that reason it is high priority.
    }
    \subsection{Stimulus/Response Sequences}
    
    \textbf{User Destination}\textit
\begin{itemize}
    \item Guest User clicks the login icon, going to the login page
    \item User presses the marketplace icon to go to that page
    \item User presses the order history icon to go to that page
    \item User presses the shopping cart icon to go to that page
    \item User searches for [generic item] and is taken to the item page
\end{itemize}

\textbf{User Not Logged In }
\begin{itemize}
    \item Guest user tries to access Marketplace, error message "user must be logged in"
    \item Guest user tries to access Shopping Cart, error message "user must be logged in"
    \item Guest user tries to access Order History, error message "user must be logged in"
    \item Guest user tries to search in the search toolbar, error message "user must be logged in"
\end{itemize}

    
    \subsection{Functional Requirements}
    \textit{
    }REQ-16:\textit{
    }There must be an icon or some link to go to the following\textit{ }pages:Marketplace, Shopping Cart, Order History.\textit{\newline
    }REQ-17:\textit{
    }Must be able to logout of the system via an icon or link within the homepage.\textit{\newline
    }
\end{subs}

